- VSCode Version: 1.7.1
- OS Version:Ubuntu 15.04

Steps to Reproduce:

1. in launch.json i set like this:

        {
            "name": "C++ Attach",
            "type": "cppdbg",
            "request": "attach",
            "program": "${workspaceRoot}/example.so",
            "processId": "${command.pickProcess}",
            "linux": {
                "MIMode": "gdb"
            },
            "osx": {
                "MIMode": "lldb"
            },
            "windows": {
                "MIMode": "gdb"
            }
        }

2. And then we run a python script which will call a C function writen in the example.so

3. We attach the python script's process and set a breakpoint in the example.cpp

I hope that it can break in the line which i set a breakpoint, but it is not. So i feel confuse that does the VSCode support such situation: "Python script call c function, and we want to debug this c function"?

- VSCode Version: 1.7.1
- OS Version: Windows 10

Steps to Reproduce:
1. Create a JS file with a file extension other than .js
e.q. "javascript.es6" with content "var fs = require('fs');"
2. Associate this file extension with "javascript"
Use UI "Select Language Mode" for that or set "files.associations": {"*.es6":"javascript"}
3. Got Error "Cannot find name 'require'"

This is because TypeScript Service associate this file as TypeScript (getScriptKindFromFileName default) if it does not get the scriptKindName from VS Code.
And VS Code only sets the scriptKindName for files without file extensions:
[extensions/typescript/src/features/bufferSyncSupport.ts](https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/blob/master/extensions/typescript/src/features/bufferSyncSupport.ts)
```
// we have no extension. So check the mode and
// set the script kind accordningly.
const ext = path.extname(this.filepath);
if (ext === '') {
	const scriptKind = Mode2ScriptKind[this.document.languageId];
	if (scriptKind) {
		args.scriptKindName = scriptKind;
	}
}
```
I think TypeScript Service should always use the scriptKind selected in VS Code, especially for file extionsions not known by the TypeScript Service.

- VSCode Version: 1.7.1 (2016-11-03T13:53:14.822Z)
- OS Version: Windows 10 - Version 1607

Steps to Reproduce:

1.  Within a javascript file create three lines that have incorrect indentation.
 - The first should be a code line
 - The second should be a comment line
 - The third should be another code line.
2. Highlight the top two lines and press Ctrl + K, Ctrl + F to format the selection.
Notice that the comment line isn't indented along with the code line
3. Undo the changes and highlight all three lines. Once again press Ctrl + K, Ctrl + F to format the selection
Notice that the comment line is now indented correctly.
4. Undo the changes and use Shift + Alt + F to format the document. The comment line is now indented as with (3).

It seems like if the last line of a selection is a comment it doesn't correctly pick up the indentation settings.

An example file is this one.

    d3.tsv("/test.tsv", (err, data) => {
        data.forEach(function (element) {
            console.log("test");
            //this is a comment
            console.log("Hello world");
        }, this);
    });
